Reference-contexts: 1 INTRODUCTION The effort of integrating local-area networks (LAN's) based on the ATM technology into the existing wide-area networks (WAN's) is well under way. Several standardization groups are currently working on specifying the ways in which the TCP/IP protocol stack is to run over ATM networks <ref> [7, 9] </ref>. As always, an effort in defining an emerging standard must be accompanied by an effort in practical implementation of the standard elements. <p> This section describes our design of the protocol stack beneath the TCP/IP. It delineates our solutions to the problems faced by this level, and evaluates their compatibility with the IETF recommendations <ref> [7] </ref>. 2.1 CONVENTIONS The ATM technology is currently in its earliest stage of development. Consequently, the role of an ATM network within a classical IP network is usually the one of a logical subnet. <p> Consequently, the role of an ATM network within a classical IP network is usually the one of a logical subnet. Although the ATM model is much more general and powerful, today it merely replaces the old Ethernet-based LAN technology. As <ref> [7] </ref> points out, the reasons for ATM being confined to traditional IP boundaries stem from the fact that IP is an old and well-established technology, while ATM is not. This paper also treats ATM networks as logical subnets. <p> For Ethernet and similar data-link-layer protocols, the address resolution is performed using the ARP [8] and InARP [2] protocols. For the ATM networks, the recommended protocols are ATMARP and InATMARP <ref> [7] </ref>. Our system does not, however, use these protocols. AT-MARP is not required for PVC-only ATM networks, and InATMARP is used exactly once, when a host attempts to find its own IP address. We decided that this single use does not justify an implementation of a whole protocol. <p> This link is used to connect IP hosts to other IP hosts. A number of hosts connected by such links comprises an ATM network. Such ATM networks are treated by the rest of the internet just like Ethernet networks, as <ref> [7] </ref> requires. It may be noted that we are using hosts to do the ATM switching, instead of dedicated switching elements. This is mandated by the original system's inflexibility: it is impossible for the user to specify which protocols are running on a network routing element.
